    The heap buffer overflow is caused by the reverse loop in print_reverse:    
                                                                                
                                                                                
     for (size_t i = v.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--) {                               
         std::printf("%d\n", v[i]);                                             
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    size_t is an unsigned integer type. Therefore this condition:               
                                                                                
                                                                                
     i >= 0                                                                     
                                                                                
                                                                                
    is always true. An unsigned value can never be less than zero.              
                                                                                
    Walkthrough of the crashing state                                           
                                                                                
    In main:                                                                    
                                                                                
                                                                                
     std::vector<int> v = {10, 20, 30};                                         
     print_reverse(v);                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    So inside print_reverse, v refers to a vector containing three elements:    
                                                                                
                                                                                
     v[0] == 10                                                                 
     v[1] == 20                                                                 
     v[2] == 30                                                                 
                                                                                
                                                                                
    The loop starts with:                                                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
     size_t i = v.size() - 1;                                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Since v.size() is 3, i is initialized to 2.                                 
                                                                                
    The loop proceeds:                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
     i == 2  // prints v[2] == 30                                               
     i == 1  // prints v[1] == 20                                               
     i == 0  // prints v[0] == 10                                               
                                                                                
                                                                                
    After the iteration where i == 0, the loop executes:                        
                                                                                
                                                                                
     i--                                                                        
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Because i is a size_t, it is unsigned. Decrementing zero does not produce   
    -1; it wraps around to the maximum representable size_t value, typically:   
                                                                                
                                                                                
     18446744073709551615                                                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Then the loop condition is checked again:                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
     i >= 0                                                                     
                                                                                
                                                                                
    That is still true, because i is unsigned.                                  
                                                                                
    So the next iteration evaluates:                                            
                                                                                
                                                                                
     v[i]                                                                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
    where i is now SIZE_MAX.                                                    
                                                                                
    That is far outside the valid range of the vector, whose valid indices are  
    only 0, 1, and 2. std::vector::operator[] does not perform bounds           
    checking, so this becomes an invalid memory read. AddressSanitizer reports  
    it as a heap buffer overflow.                                               
                                                                                
    The stack trace shows the crash at:                                         
                                                                                
                                                                                
     std::printf("%d\n", v[i]);                                                 
                                                                                
                                                                                
    but the actual bad operation is evaluating v[i], before printf is called.   
                                                                                
    There is a second related bug for the empty-vector case:                    
                                                                                
                                                                                
     std::vector<int> empty;                                                    
     print_reverse(empty);                                                      
                                                                                
                                                                                
    For an empty vector:                                                        
                                                                                
                                                                                
     v.size() == 0                                                              
                                                                                
                                                                                
    So this expression:                                                         
                                                                                
                                                                                
     v.size() - 1                                                               
                                                                                
                                                                                
    also underflows immediately, producing SIZE_MAX. The first access would     
    then be:                                                                    
                                                                                
                                                                                
     v[SIZE_MAX]                                                                
                                                                                
                                                                                
    which is also invalid.                                                      
                                                                                
    In this run, the program crashes during the first call to print_reverse(v)  
    before it ever reaches the empty-vector regression case.                    
                                                                                
    Minimal local fix                                                           
                                                                                
    Use a reverse loop idiom that works with unsigned indices:                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void print_reverse(const std::vector<int>& v) {                     
         for (size_t i = v.size(); i-- > 0;) {                                  
             std::printf("%d\n", v[i]);                                         
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This works because i starts one past the last valid index. The condition    
    decrements first logically for the loop body, and the loop body only runs   
    when the previous value was greater than zero.                              
                                                                                
    For v.size() == 3, it prints indices:                                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
     2, 1, 0                                                                    
                                                                                
                                                                                
    For v.size() == 0, the condition is false immediately, so the loop body is  
    skipped.                                                                    
                                                                                
    More thorough root-cause fix                                                
                                                                                
    The root cause is manually writing reverse index arithmetic with an         
    unsigned loop variable. A safer and more idiomatic C++ fix is to use        
    reverse iterators:                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void print_reverse(const std::vector<int>& v) {                     
         for (auto it = v.rbegin(); it != v.rend(); ++it) {                     
             std::printf("%d\n", *it);                                          
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This avoids unsigned underflow entirely and naturally handles empty         
    vectors.                                                                    
                                                                                
    Alternatively, with a range-based loop over reverse iterators in            
    C++20-style code:                                                           
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #include <cstdio>                                                          
     #include <vector>                                                          
                                                                                
     static void print_reverse(const std::vector<int>& v) {                     
         for (auto it = v.rbegin(); it != v.rend(); ++it) {                     
             std::printf("%d\n", *it);                                          
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
    Replace the loop with either of these safe versions:                        
                                                                                
    Minimal local fix:                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void print_reverse(const std::vector<int>& v) {                     
         for (size_t i = v.size(); i-- > 0;) {                                  
             std::printf("%d\n", v[i]);                                         
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Preferred root-cause fix:                                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void print_reverse(const std::vector<int>& v) {                     
         for (auto it = v.rbegin(); it != v.rend(); ++it) {                     
             std::printf("%d\n", *it);                                          
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
